1	\chapter{The relative Picard functor as an abelian-group-valued presheaf}
2	\label{chap:Picard_FunctorAb}
3	
4	This chapter is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}. The relative Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} is set-valued; the construction merely forgets the abelian-group structure that the values $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ carry by definition. To set up Phase~C step~3 (\'etale sheafification) and any future cohomology-of-Picard-presheaf work, we need an abelian-group-valued variant whose values agree on the nose with the set-valued ones.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} via the same path as Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Relative Picard functor, abelian-group valued]
12	  \label{def:Pic_functorAb}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb}
14	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
15	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{abelian-group-valued relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
16	  \[
17	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \;\colon\; (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \AddCommGrpCat,\qquad
18	    S \;\longmapsto\; \mathtt{AddCommGrpCat.of}\;\bigl(\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)\bigr),
19	  \]
20	  with morphisms induced by the quotient pull-back maps defined in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.
21	\end{definition}
22	
23	\begin{remark}
24	  The underlying-set functor of $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ agrees on the nose with the set-valued Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} computes the same group quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ but discards the group structure. The forget-and-recover natural iso (Definition~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare} below) records this. It is needed to transport later results (e.g.\ representability) between the two flavours.
25	\end{remark}
26	
27	\section{Forget-and-recover natural iso}
28	
29	\begin{definition}\leanok
30	[$\PicardFunctorAb$ recovers $\PicardFunctor$ along forget]
31	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
32	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.forgetCompare}
33	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
34	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. Then there is a natural isomorphism of set-valued functors
35	  \[
36	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \,\circ\, \forget \AddCommGrpCat \;\cong\; \PicardFunctor\, C
37	  \]
38	  in $(\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \to \mathrm{Set}$.
39	\end{definition}
40	
41	\begin{proof}
42	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
43	  \leanok
44	  Both sides have the same object at $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$ --- the quotient set $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ --- and the same map on morphisms --- the quotient pull-back. The additive wrapper is type-equal to its underlying multiplicative quotient, so the two functors agree on the nose at the underlying-type level. The natural iso is therefore the identity natural transformation in disguise.
45	\end{proof}
46	
47	\begin{lemma}\leanok
48	[Forget-evaluation simp lemma]
49	  \label{lem:PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
50	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
51	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
52	  For every $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$,
53	  \[
54	    (\forget\,\AddCommGrpCat).\mathrm{obj}\,\bigl((\PicardFunctorAb\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S\bigr) \;=\; (\PicardFunctor\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S.
55	  \]
56	\end{lemma}
57	
58	\begin{proof}
59	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
60	  \leanok
61	  Definitionally true: both sides are the underlying carrier of the quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$.
62	\end{proof}
63	
64	\section{\'Etale sheafification}
65	
66	The \'etale-sheafified relative Picard functor is built on top of $\PicardFunctorAb$. The Mathlib gap that previously blocked this (sheafification for the \'etale topology over $\Spec k$ valued in $\AddCommGrpCat$) closed in current Mathlib. The only remaining gymnastic is universe-pinning: the inferable sheafification is at value-universe $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$, while $\PicardFunctorAb$ lands at $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}$; we bridge the gap by post-composing with the universe lift.
67	
68	\begin{definition}\leanok
69	[\'Etale-sheafified relative Picard functor]
70	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified}
71	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.etaleSheafified}
72	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
73	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{\'etale-sheafified relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the \'etale sheaf on $\Sch_k$ obtained by sheafifying $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ post-composed with the natural universe lift $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\} \to \AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$.
74	\end{definition}
75	
76	\begin{proof}
77	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
78	  \leanok
79	  Apply the Mathlib sheafification left-adjoint to the universe-lifted presheaf. The two sheafification instances are now inferable in current Mathlib for the \'etale topology over $\Spec k$ valued in $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$, so sheafification types out without extra hypotheses.
80	\end{proof}
81	
82	\section{Use in the project}
83	
84	Definitions~\ref{def:Pic_functorAb} and~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified} set up the codomain needed for:
85	
86	\begin{itemize}
87	  \item The \'etale-sheafified version of the relative Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: the input shape required by Grothendieck's representability machinery is a sheaf for the \'etale topology, not a presheaf.
88	  \item Comparison with the Jacobian's $\Pic^0$ as a group scheme: the connected-component-of-identity of the representing scheme is a group object in $\Sch_k$.
89	  \item Direct definition of $H^n$-of-the-Picard-presheaf if a future iteration wants to expose it as a derived functor.
90	\end{itemize}
91	
92	The representability theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} carries over verbatim once the \'etale sheafification of $\PicardFunctorAb$ has been constructed; the four Jacobian sorries are the same as before, and the remaining gating obstruction for representability is the line-bundle refinement of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}. This chapter does \emph{not} add a representability theorem of its own --- the present chapter is the codomain change plus the \'etale sheafification.
93	
94	\section{Mathlib gap}
95	
96	Mathlib has every constituent for this chapter:
97	\begin{itemize}
98	  \item Bundling of abelian groups and homomorphisms into the categorical shape.
99	  \item Commutative-group structure on quotients of commutative groups.
100	  \item This project's Picard functor (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}) for the underlying construction and the quotient pull-back functoriality.
101	\end{itemize}
102	
103	The chapter therefore introduces no new sorries beyond the single definition itself; the prover task is to wrap the Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} construction in the abelian-group category and discharge the resulting functoriality obligations (which reduce to those already proved).
